<h1><a class='u' href='#___top' title='click to go to top of document'
name="NAME"
>NAME <img alt='^' src='http://st.pimg.net/tucs/img/up.gif'></a></h1>

<p>Throwable - a role for classes that can be thrown</p>

<h1><a class='u' href='#___top' title='click to go to top of document'
name="VERSION"
>VERSION <img alt='^' src='http://st.pimg.net/tucs/img/up.gif'></a></h1>

<p>version 0.102080</p>

<h1><a class='u' href='#___top' title='click to go to top of document'
name="SYNOPSIS"
>SYNOPSIS <img alt='^' src='http://st.pimg.net/tucs/img/up.gif'></a></h1>

<pre class="sh_perl">  package Redirect;
  use Moose;
  with &#39;Throwable&#39;;

  has url =&#62; (is =&#62; &#39;ro&#39;);</pre>

<p>...then later...</p>

<pre class="sh_perl">  Redirect-&#62;throw({ url =&#62; $url });</pre>

<h1><a class='u' href='#___top' title='click to go to top of document'
name="DESCRIPTION"
>DESCRIPTION <img alt='^' src='http://st.pimg.net/tucs/img/up.gif'></a></h1>

<p>Throwable is a role for classes that are meant to be thrown as exceptions to standard program flow. It is very simple and does only two things: saves any previous value for <code>$@</code> and calls <code>die $self</code>.</p>

<h1><a class='u' href='#___top' title='click to go to top of document'
name="ATTRIBUTES"
>ATTRIBUTES <img alt='^' src='http://st.pimg.net/tucs/img/up.gif'></a></h1>

<h2><a class='u' href='#___top' title='click to go to top of document'
name="previous_exception"
>previous_exception</a></h2>

<p>This attribute is created automatically, and stores the value of <code>$@</code> when the Throwable object is created.</p>

<h1><a class='u' href='#___top' title='click to go to top of document'
name="METHODS"
>METHODS <img alt='^' src='http://st.pimg.net/tucs/img/up.gif'></a></h1>

<h2><a class='u' href='#___top' title='click to go to top of document'
name="throw"
>throw</a></h2>

<pre class="sh_perl">  Something::Throwable-&#62;throw({ attr =&#62; $value });</pre>

<p>This method will call new, passing all arguments along to new, and will then use the created object as the only argument to <code>die</code>.</p>

<p>If called on an object that does Throwable, the object will be rethrown.</p>

